126
00:14:17,122 --> 00:14:28,228
Hi, one of the things that the subcommittee looked at as we looked at this question was the case of Lowell, Massachusetts.

127
00:14:29,168 --> 00:14:32,410
Lowell, Massachusetts, like Medford, has eight wards.

128
00:14:32,870 --> 00:14:43,015
And in 2017, a lawsuit was filed against the city alleging that their at-large system violated the Voting Rights Act of 1965.

129
00:14:44,776 --> 00:14:51,560
by denying Asian American and Hispanic and Latino voters an equal opportunity to elect candidates of their choice.

130
00:14:53,361 --> 00:14:57,663
In 2019, without conceding a violation of the Voting Rights Act, the city settled.

131
00:14:59,083 --> 00:15:05,907
So right now, Lowell currently has hybrid ward representation for city council and school committee.

132
00:15:08,424 --> 00:15:12,527
And we were interested in this as we looked at Medford's demographics.

133
00:15:13,327 --> 00:15:24,957
And when we learned that Medford has at least has one majority minority ward and a population that is continually becoming more diverse, this was an interesting case for us to look at.

134
00:15:26,238 --> 00:15:34,004
Because it's also research has also shown that ward representation increases diversity in elected officials.

135
00:15:35,245 --> 00:15:35,565
Thank you.

136
00:15:37,842 --> 00:15:38,162
Thank you.

137
00:15:39,963 --> 00:16:04,152
So in order to do our conclusions, we looked at some strengths and challenges and we're showing you what we got from surveys, emails, comments, discussion, but in no way do these reflect necessarily the opinions of the subcommittee or the charter committee.

138
00:16:04,692 --> 00:16:09,834
But we're going to present a bunch of them to you now just to provoke some thought.

139
00:16:10,294 --> 00:16:12,214
And then we'll have some question and answers.

140
00:16:12,274 --> 00:16:15,255
Hopefully, you all have some really good question, answers, and comments.

141
00:16:15,295 --> 00:16:18,997
So let's go through the list of strengths.

142
00:16:20,417 --> 00:16:23,698
This would be the strengths of going to ward representation.

143
00:16:24,438 --> 00:16:28,239
It guarantees that at least one council would come from each ward.

144
00:16:30,180 --> 00:16:35,326
Fewer candidates on the ballot may make the voting process easier to use.

145
00:16:37,749 --> 00:16:40,512
Makes running for ward office more accessible.

146
00:16:41,493 --> 00:16:48,941
Cost of running campaign and campaign ground game gets reduced due to a smaller voter pool in each ward.

147
00:16:57,502 --> 00:16:58,423
Next one, okay.

148
00:16:58,883 --> 00:17:11,453
A small constituency gives ward counselors the ability to foster more direct relationships with residents and gives residents the opportunity for improved communication with their ward rep.

149
00:17:12,114 --> 00:17:13,535
We heard that a lot in the surveys.

150
00:17:16,128 --> 00:17:17,908
Eliminates duplication of work.

151
00:17:20,249 --> 00:17:38,413
I guess to explain that it really has to do with chairing certain committees, subcommittees of the council and being able to assume that a citizen in a particular ward would go to their ward rep first and not go to somebody outside their ward first.

152
00:17:38,453 --> 00:17:42,054
So hopefully there's not two councilors working on the same issue at the same time.

153
00:17:42,814 --> 00:17:42,994
Next.

154
00:17:45,120 --> 00:17:48,361
World representation increases diversity of representation.

155
00:17:49,281 --> 00:17:57,523
At large elections and minority representation in local governments is the information we gathered from the American Journal of Political Science.

156
00:17:59,704 --> 00:18:04,625
Increased number of counselors means more individuals to fulfill the work of the council.

157
00:18:04,965 --> 00:18:07,546
This again is chairmanships and things like that.

158
00:18:09,567 --> 00:18:14,055
at large representation will still exist with a hybrid council.

159
00:18:14,676 --> 00:18:21,348
So there will be several slots available for an entire city at large campaign.

160
00:18:23,237 --> 00:18:29,564
It's easier to address needs in each neighborhood because those candidates would come from that neighborhood and those counselors.

161
00:18:30,465 --> 00:18:34,951
The hybrid reward system is the predominant method throughout the Commonwealth.

162
00:18:35,271 --> 00:18:44,041
Approximately 80% of local governments in Massachusetts use that form of government.

163
00:18:46,102 --> 00:18:47,903
Okay, little challenges now.

164
00:18:48,384 --> 00:18:55,628
Ward representatives focus more on their ward needs and not those of the whole city.

165
00:18:57,149 --> 00:18:58,130
Self-explanatory.

166
00:18:58,870 --> 00:19:02,613
Voters cannot vote for or against the entire council.

167
00:19:03,614 --> 00:19:08,257
You would only be voting for at-large positions and the candidates from your ward.

168
00:19:09,838 --> 00:19:13,180
Ward boundaries may not reflect how communities see themselves.

169
00:19:15,519 --> 00:19:20,721
Ward representation may result in unequal workloads for counselors.

170
00:19:20,741 --> 00:19:30,206
And this has to do with the makeup of each ward, what's in the ward, residential, education, buildings, businesses.

171
00:19:31,046 --> 00:19:33,987
So they're not all equal in terms of what goes on in their wards.

172
00:19:36,629 --> 00:19:42,631
If you don't support the ward candidate who gets elected, will they serve your need?

173
00:19:43,292 --> 00:19:43,752
No comment.

174
00:19:45,779 --> 00:19:51,364
Ward representation may limit voter candidate options, because you don't get to vote for everybody.

175
00:19:53,405 --> 00:19:58,149
Some people believe that all city councilors should represent the whole city.

176
00:20:00,671 --> 00:20:03,293
Ward representation may divide the city.

177
00:20:05,515 --> 00:20:08,437
Adding additional councilors would increase the city's budget.

178
00:20:09,058 --> 00:20:15,363
Just do the math, and if you have seven now, we go to 11 or 13, that's additional salaries.

179
00:20:16,886 --> 00:20:22,408
Okay, I want to thank the committee for doing such a great job of getting down to the details.

180
00:20:22,468 --> 00:20:31,192
Now it's time to listen to what your comments are, your questions, so we can have a really great discussion about where we go from here.

181
00:20:44,352 --> 00:20:50,258
So if you have a question, comment, concern, you can just raise your hand on Zoom and we'll get to you.

182
00:20:50,278 --> 00:20:52,600
