331
00:36:37,237 --> 00:36:40,318
These seem to be significant numbers to me.

332
00:36:40,879 --> 00:36:56,084
And I'm just curious, have you done any research about the ethnicity or racial makeup of the councils in the last, I don't know, 25, 50 years or school committee?

333
00:36:56,524 --> 00:37:05,967
Have there been members of either of those two bodies who have been people of color or foreign born?

334
00:37:07,470 --> 00:37:07,870
Thank you.

335
00:37:09,532 --> 00:37:10,714
That's a great question.

336
00:37:11,915 --> 00:37:21,285
We have not, we did not, for this presentation, pull together the race, ethnicity of our elected officials, but we did...

337
00:37:30,872 --> 00:37:40,878
I think you have to go back a bit, and I'm certainly happy to do a little bit of that digging for you, Steve.

338
00:37:41,339 --> 00:37:51,666
Other than what we recently have of the past council or two, I think we have to go back a little bit to find some diversity.

339
00:37:53,787 --> 00:37:54,868
I know that there's been a bit

340
00:37:57,967 --> 00:38:01,390
a while back and I'm happy to dig into that a little bit more for you.

341
00:38:07,835 --> 00:38:11,297
I would have Steve is whether the city actually collects that data.

342
00:38:11,317 --> 00:38:18,523
Because you do have to be careful about assigning race to people if they're not identifying what their race is.

343
00:38:18,603 --> 00:38:22,346
So that would be one question I would have is, does the city collect that data?

344
00:38:22,866 --> 00:38:23,967
Is it something we could find?

345
00:38:24,992 --> 00:38:32,550
I think it's more kind of what is sort of obvious, which is not the best way to be doing things.

346
00:38:33,482 --> 00:38:39,124
Yeah, I don't know that the city necessarily collects that.

347
00:38:39,184 --> 00:38:42,044
The city clerk may have some of that information.

348
00:38:42,064 --> 00:38:52,847
I think it would be more, you know, from what one would observe, which is not necessarily the best way to go about doing things.

349
00:38:55,588 --> 00:38:59,269
I can ask the city clerk, but I don't really think that there's any data there.

350
00:39:04,580 --> 00:39:05,116
when I get back.

351
00:39:08,298 --> 00:39:12,841
So I appreciate adding more work to your load.

352
00:39:14,523 --> 00:39:15,223
Thank you for that.

353
00:39:15,263 --> 00:39:18,485
You're working very hard on this and it's much appreciated.

354
00:39:20,647 --> 00:39:36,719
I'm just wondering if you feel that having ward representation in a hybrid system would give more representation to people who have not been represented very well at the council or the school committee.

355
00:39:40,605 --> 00:39:48,689
The research seems to suggest that ward representation does create more diverse elected representation in a city.

356
00:39:48,809 --> 00:39:53,751
So that's, we have in the slides, which you can look at, we have a paper that we cite.

357
00:39:54,411 --> 00:40:07,377
So it has been, when there's been civil rights challenges around voting rights, that has been one of the solutions that has come out of legal processes.

358
00:40:08,713 --> 00:40:10,033
Yeah, I agree.

359
00:40:10,233 --> 00:40:12,074
I think Jean said that well.

360
00:40:12,614 --> 00:40:26,477
It also, as also was pointed out in the slide, it makes running for office more accessible because it's financially more accessible and there's less ground to cover in a ward.

361
00:40:27,257 --> 00:40:30,898
The other piece is that, as we saw in the Lowell case,

362
00:40:32,767 --> 00:40:45,732
It's also the voters, when you have a majority minority ward, if there's ward representation, then that ward has an opportunity to elect a candidate of their choice.

363
00:40:46,872 --> 00:40:49,954
And that's what we saw in the Lowell case.

364
00:40:49,994 --> 00:40:56,136
And that was one of the reasons that that case came to the fore and was settled the way it was.

365
00:40:57,965 --> 00:41:00,447
The only other, oh, go ahead.

366
00:41:00,467 --> 00:41:02,129
I just want to add quickly, Steve, when you

367
00:41:04,212 --> 00:41:16,014
When we make any kind of decision like this, the committee was very conscious of not putting our opinions into this presentation to make it a clear expectation.

368
00:41:16,434 --> 00:41:20,475
We will be voicing our opinions soon.

369
00:41:21,915 --> 00:41:28,896
But to your point, when you make a change like this in any kind, you need to set up measurements to see if the changes work.

370
00:41:30,777 --> 00:41:31,397
Right away,

371
00:41:32,237 --> 00:41:36,601
every ward will have a representative if we go to ward representation.

372
00:41:37,122 --> 00:41:39,204
So that's a guaranteed fix.

373
00:41:39,604 --> 00:41:49,113
So we've already improved, but to your point, I think we do need to, and we will establish more goals to measure against the decisions that we make.

374
00:41:49,534 --> 00:41:50,775
I hope that answers your question.

375
00:41:51,746 --> 00:41:56,309
And the only other point I wanted to make is Medford is becoming more diverse over time.

376
00:41:56,689 --> 00:42:03,574
We didn't have the data to present the trends, but over time we are becoming more diverse, not less.

377
00:42:03,614 --> 00:42:09,177
So we will probably see other wards increasing in their diversity.

378
00:42:11,419 --> 00:42:13,540
Steve, did you have any more questions or was that it?

379
00:42:13,600 --> 00:42:15,221
If you have a question, raise your hand again.

380
00:42:15,241 --> 00:42:18,103
Okay.

381
00:42:25,311 --> 00:42:28,792
Emily.

382
00:42:28,812 --> 00:42:30,132
Hi, thank you all for doing this.

383
00:42:30,212 --> 00:42:31,272
We appreciate your work.

384
00:42:32,733 --> 00:42:43,995
I have a question about I recognize that this presentation is about City Council and the prospect of there being ward based representation for just that body.

385
00:42:44,716 --> 00:42:50,157
But I was wondering if you have plans to look into school committee and what that would entail in the future.

386
00:42:56,350 --> 00:43:06,357
Yes, we are this week, I believe the first meeting of this school committee subcommittee will happen, actually it's next week.

387
00:43:07,158 --> 00:43:19,587
And they will be digging into that topic and looking at maybe some of the similar things we looked at, but also different things because it's a school committee has different issues.

388
00:43:19,687 --> 00:43:21,749
So yes, we are definitely going to be doing that.

389
00:43:23,184 --> 00:43:35,232
Okay, and I just have one more follow up question, which is, what is the timeline you all have in mind for, this is more of a general question about your work and your presenting of your work.

390
00:43:35,472 --> 00:43:40,255
When do you expect to present your sort of final recommendations?

391
00:43:40,855 --> 00:43:41,676
And how do you do that?

392
00:43:41,736 --> 00:43:42,676
Who do you present it to?

393
00:43:42,716 --> 00:43:43,697
And where does it go from there?

394
00:43:45,058 --> 00:43:45,478
Thank you.

395
00:43:46,818 --> 00:43:52,800
Our target date is about a year from now, the fall of 2024.

396
00:43:53,780 --> 00:43:56,161
That could change, but that's what we're aiming for.

397
00:43:58,361 --> 00:44:06,664
And what we will be doing is presenting first to the City Council, and then the City Council will make a presentation.

398
00:44:06,704 --> 00:44:07,904
We'll create a final report.

399
00:44:07,924 --> 00:44:12,005
The City Council will look at the recommendations, vote on them,

400
00:44:12,999 --> 00:44:14,781
and then it goes to the mayor.

401
00:44:15,302 --> 00:44:18,306
And if it clears those hurdles, then it goes to the state house.

402
00:44:19,828 --> 00:44:24,293
And at that point, if it clears the state house hurdle, then it goes to the voters.

403
00:44:27,217 --> 00:44:27,918
Excellent, thank you.

404
00:44:31,102 --> 00:44:31,322
Micah?

405
00:44:33,675 --> 00:44:35,896
Yeah, I'm just curious.

406
00:44:36,677 --> 00:44:49,265
You alluded to it really briefly, but are there any specific financial constraints that you're operating under for the increase in the council size?

407
00:44:49,705 --> 00:44:53,387
Or is it mostly just don't explode the budget, obviously?

408
00:44:55,366 --> 00:45:05,209
Yeah, it would be nice to just hear if you could speak more to the finances of it too, because it is potentially a very large financial jump, and how we're going to be able to budget for it.

409
00:45:06,729 --> 00:45:12,050
Which by that said, though, I still just want to be clear, I'm super in support of having the word representation.

410
00:45:12,070 --> 00:45:14,371
I think it makes a hell of a lot more sense than what we have right now.

411
00:45:22,444 --> 00:45:25,305
Well, thankfully, Micah, that's not under our umbrella.

412
00:45:28,465 --> 00:45:30,146
It is a concern, absolutely.

413
00:45:33,566 --> 00:45:39,207
I'm sure it'll be a consideration for those people who vote, and as it goes up the ladder.

414
00:45:39,768 --> 00:45:44,088
But it's not something that we've considered.

415
00:45:44,128 --> 00:45:51,310
We know it is an issue to add four to six members to a city council.

416
00:45:52,130 --> 00:45:56,673
But we also, my opinion is you can always decrease salaries, too.

417
00:45:59,195 --> 00:46:11,583
Yeah, as Ron said, that's not under our umbrella, but in the scheme of the city budget, I don't think that four councilors will explode the city budget.

418
00:46:14,184 --> 00:46:15,225
But, you know, that's...

419
00:46:18,305 --> 00:46:22,029
We're looking at what's best for the governance of the city.

420
00:46:22,309 --> 00:46:28,094
And that's so that's not really part of our wheelhouse that we're looking at.

421
00:46:29,215 --> 00:46:33,839
Yeah, I want to repeat something that Ron said earlier, which was there's a cost of doing this and a cost of not doing it.

422
00:46:33,859 --> 00:46:43,148
